   137	| `"doc"` (synthetic test fixture from `tests/perf_gates.rs:350`) | `article` (coerced) |
   138	| anything else         | **writer error** — fail the projection outcome (`EngineError::Storage`); do not silently default. |
   139	
   140	Rationale for the `doc` -> `article` coercion: AC-013 seeds
   141	synthetic doc-shaped bodies (long-form text) that are the most
   142	semantically aligned with the `article` source within the locked
   143	6-value set. The coercion (a) preserves the partition_key
   144	utility for the AC-013 fixture rows (they aggregate under a real
   145	source_type bucket the corpus-build work will also populate),
   146	(b) avoids any test churn — the fixture continues to write
   147	`kind="doc"`; only the resolved `source_type` differs, (c)
   148	matches what `CORPUS-1` (CNN/DailyMail acquisition, commit
   149	`27ab8df`) will land as the production article source. The
   150	coercion is writer-internal; the canonical `kind` value is
   151	preserved verbatim in the `kind` metadata column (and in
   152	`_fathomdb_vector_rows`), so any consumer needing to distinguish
   153	fixture rows from corpus rows can still do so by reading `kind`.
   154	
   155	Rejected alternatives:
   156	
   157	- "Add `doc` as a 7th `source_type` value" — extends the
   158	  HITL-locked vocabulary without authorization. This was the
   159	  original draft and is the blocking finding in the codex
   160	  verdict (`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-review-20260527T132959Z.md`
   161	  finding 1).
   162	- "Rename the fixture kind from `doc` to one of the 6 locked
   163	  values" — touches every test that reads the AC-013 fixture
   164	  (larger blast radius than a writer-side coercion).
   165	- "Leave `source_type` nullable for unmapped kinds" — loses the
   166	  partition_key benefit for the AC-013 fixture and breaks the
   167	  "partition_key is locked" guarantee in HITL Q5.
   168	
   169	Citation: HITL lock at
   170	`dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md:135-137` (vocabulary +
   171	"supersedes the `kind` default in the Pack 1 handoff").
   172	
   173	The mapping is implemented in a single Rust helper:
   174	
   175	```rust
   176	fn resolve_source_type(kind: &str) -> Result<&'static str, EngineError> {
   177	    Ok(match kind {
   178	        "email" => "email",
   179	        "article" => "article",
   180	        "paper" => "paper",
   181	        "meeting" => "meeting",
   182	        "note" => "note",
   183	        "todo" => "todo",
   184	        // Synthetic AC-013 test fixture; coerced to "article" so
   185	        // the 6-value HITL lock holds. See D3 rationale above.
   186	        "doc" => "article",
   187	        _ => return Err(EngineError::Storage),
   188	    })
   189	}
   190	```
   191	
   192	(no allocator pressure; returns `&'static str`; used at both
   193	writer sites in D7.)
   194	
   195	## D4 — NOT NULL + migration strategy
   196	
   197	vec0 virtual tables in sqlite-vec `=0.1.7` (this repo's pin)
   198	support neither `ALTER TABLE ... ADD COLUMN` (a SQLite-level
   199	rule for virtual tables — https://www.sqlite.org/vtab.html) nor
   200	`ALTER TABLE ... RENAME` (rename support landed in sqlite-vec
   201	`v0.1.10-alpha.2`, April 2026, per the sqlite-vec release
   202	history). The migration is therefore a `DROP TABLE` + recreate
   203	under the same name. Repopulation must be **synchronous and
   204	in-transaction**, copying the existing f32 blobs verbatim — it
   205	must NOT go through the engine's async rebuild driver.
   206	
   207	**Decision: land NOT NULL constraints from the start. The
   208	migration is a single SQL migration step that (a) stages the
   209	existing f32 rows + kind into a regular SQL table, (b) drops
   210	and recreates `vector_default` with the new schema under the
   211	same name, (c) repopulates `vector_default` from the staging
   212	table with `vec_quantize_binary` evaluated SQL-side at INSERT
   213	bind, and (d) drops the staging table — all inside the migration
   214	framework's `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` / `COMMIT` envelope. The writer
   215	enforces non-nullability from commit zero.**
   216	
   217	Schema versioning is owned by the engine's real migration
   218	framework: `migrate_with_event_sink(...)` at
   219	`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:1238`, which is a
   220	thin re-export of `fathomdb_schema::migrate_with_event_sink`
   221	implemented at `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:218-271`.
   222	`apply_one` (`src/rust/crates/fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`)
   223	wraps each migration step in `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` ... `COMMIT`,
   224	calling `conn.execute_batch(migration.sql)` followed by
   225	`pragma_update(PRAGMA_USER_VERSION, step_id)`, and rolling back
   226	on any error. `Migration` itself is `{ step_id: u32, sql:
   227	&'static str }` (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:51-54`) — pure SQL,
   228	no Rust callback hook. The new vec0 schema lands as a new
   229	`fathomdb_schema::Migration` step appended to the existing
   230	migration array passed into `open_with_migrations`
   231	(`lib.rs:1119-1131`); `migrate_with_event_sink` bumps
   232	`PRAGMA user_version` on commit and gates re-entry on the same
   233	sentinel, so re-opens are naturally idempotent. The previously
   234	proposed `operational_mutations` schema stamp is **not** the
   235	schema-version owner — that collection is excise audit rows
   236	(`lib.rs:2217-2221`) — and is dropped from the design.
   237	
   238	Migration step (Pack 1) — single SQL blob, executed atomically
   239	by `apply_one` (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`):
   240	
   241	```sql
   242	-- Step body. Runs inside BEGIN IMMEDIATE ... COMMIT supplied
   243	-- by apply_one. <dim> is rendered at migration-build time
   244	-- (768 for the default profile, see ensure_vector_partition at
   245	-- lib.rs:3278-3283). <now> is the migration timestamp (UNIX
   246	-- seconds), rendered by the engine when the migration array is
   247	-- constructed at open_with_migrations (lib.rs:1119-1131); the
   248	-- whole corpus is backfilled with the same created_at value.
   249	
   250	-- 1. Stage existing f32 blobs + kind into a regular SQL table.
   251	--    _fathomdb_vector_rows.kind is the source of truth for the
   252	--    existing rows' kind (writer site at lib.rs:2845-2853).
   253	CREATE TABLE _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0 (
   254	  rowid     INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,
   255	  embedding BLOB NOT NULL,
   256	  kind      TEXT NOT NULL
   257	);
   258	INSERT INTO _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0(rowid, embedding, kind)
   259	SELECT v.rowid, v.embedding, r.kind
   260	  FROM vector_default v
   261	  JOIN _fathomdb_vector_rows r ON r.rowid = v.rowid;
   262	
   263	-- 2. Drop the old vec0 table and recreate under the same name.
   264	DROP TABLE vector_default;
   265	CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE vector_default USING vec0(
   266	  embedding float[<dim>],
   267	  embedding_bin bit[<dim>],
   268	  source_type TEXT partition key,
   269	  kind TEXT,
   270	  created_at INTEGER
   271	);
   272	
   273	-- 3. Repopulate from staging. vec_quantize_binary runs SQL-side
   274	--    once per row against the existing f32 blob; source_type is
   275	--    coerced from kind via the D3 mapping using a CASE
   276	--    expression. Any kind outside the D3 vocabulary raises
   277	--    SQLITE_CONSTRAINT (NOT NULL) on source_type, which aborts
   278	--    the migration and rolls back the whole step — matching the
   279	--    "writer error on unknown kind" rule in D3.
   280	INSERT INTO vector_default(
   281	  rowid, embedding, embedding_bin, source_type, kind, created_at
   282	)
   283	SELECT
   284	  s.rowid,
   285	  s.embedding,
   286	  vec_quantize_binary(s.embedding),
   287	  CASE s.kind
   288	    WHEN 'email'   THEN 'email'
   289	    WHEN 'article' THEN 'article'
   290	    WHEN 'paper'   THEN 'paper'
   291	    WHEN 'meeting' THEN 'meeting'
   292	    WHEN 'note'    THEN 'note'
   293	    WHEN 'todo'    THEN 'todo'
   294	    WHEN 'doc'     THEN 'article'  -- AC-013 fixture coercion; see D3.
   295	    ELSE NULL
   296	  END AS source_type,
   297	  s.kind,
   298	  <now>
   299	FROM _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0 s;
   300	
   301	-- 4. Drop the staging table.
   302	DROP TABLE _fathomdb_vector_migration_v0_7_0;
   303	```
   304	
   305	Why the D3 mapping is inlined in SQL (and not a Rust loop): the
   306	`Migration` shape at `fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:51-54` is
   307	`{ step_id, sql: &'static str }` — pure SQL, no Rust callback
   308	extension point. The CASE WHEN above is the literal byte-for-byte
   309	transcription of the D3 mapping table; a Rust-side loop would
   310	require extending the schema crate's migration trait (a
   311	larger-blast-radius change that this slice does not authorize).
   312	The CASE shape also avoids registering an ad-hoc Rust scalar
   313	function on the migration connection. The D3 helper
   314	`resolve_source_type` (defined in this memo for the writer
   315	sites D5/D7) is the canonical lookup at write time; the CASE
   316	above is the migration-time mirror of that table and must be
   317	kept in lockstep with it — P1-IMPL adds a co-located assertion
   318	in tests/migration coverage to catch drift.
   319	
   320	Properties of this migration step:
   321	
   322	- **Synchronous.** All four sub-steps run inside the same
   323	  `apply_one` transaction (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`),
   324	  on the migration thread, before `migrate_with_event_sink`
   325	  returns. There is no async hand-off.
   326	- **No embedder rerun.** The f32 blobs are copied verbatim from
   327	  `vector_default.embedding` into the staging table and back
   328	  out. The embedder is never invoked.
   329	- **`vec_quantize_binary` call site.** SQL-side at the
   330	  repopulation `INSERT`'s SELECT projection, once per row,
   331	  evaluated against the f32 blob already materialised in the
   332	  staging row. No Rust-side bit math; no double scan of the
   333	  source blob.
   334	- **Atomicity.** `apply_one` wraps the whole SQL blob in
   335	  `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` ... `COMMIT` and `ROLLBACK`s on any error
   336	  (`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:273-288`). If any sub-step
   337	  fails (e.g. an unmapped `kind` value triggers the NULL ->
   338	  NOT-NULL constraint at sub-step 3), the migration is rolled
   339	  back, `PRAGMA user_version` stays at the previous value, and
   340	  the next open re-attempts the migration cleanly. The staging
   341	  table is part of the same transaction and is dropped on
   342	  rollback alongside the would-be new `vector_default`.
   343	- **NOT NULL enforcement at write time.** vec0 metadata columns
   344	  do not have a declarative `NOT NULL` constraint in the
   345	  sqlite-vec DDL surface
   346	  (https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html);
   347	  non-nullability is contract-enforced by the migration and by
   348	  the D5/D7 writers. Pack 1 writers always supply all five
   349	  metadata columns; the migration always supplies them (or
   350	  fails atomically). No row can land with a NULL.
   351	
   352	Migration cost: dominated by two sequential scans of the
   353	existing 3 GB f32 corpus on the 1 M-row fixture — one for the
   354	staging `INSERT ... SELECT` (sub-step 1) and one for the
   355	repopulation `INSERT ... SELECT` (sub-step 3). The
   356	`vec_quantize_binary` work is a sign-bit fold per coordinate,
   357	negligible relative to the I/O. The working budget remains the
   358	60-90 s estimate from ADR § 4. The migration **does not** re-run
   359	the embedder, so the AC-013 562 s seed time
   360	(`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PERF-EXP-W4.1-ac013-canonical-output.json`)
   361	is **not** a comparable baseline — that figure includes embedder
   362	work this migration avoids by construction. A concrete
   363	measurement lands in P1-IMPL's GREEN gate.
   364	
   365	Idempotence: `PRAGMA user_version` already guards re-entry
   366	(`fathomdb-schema/src/lib.rs:234`, `:277`). On the second open
   367	the migration step is skipped because `migration.step_id <=
   368	before`, and `vector_default` keeps the rows from the first
   369	pass.
   370	
   371	### Rejected alternative — repopulate via `Engine::rebuild_vec0` / `RebuildKind::Vec0`
   372	
   373	The fix-1 draft of D4 proposed driving repopulation through
   374	`Engine::rebuild_vec0` (`lib.rs:1947`), which calls
   375	`run_rebuild` -> `rebuild_shadow_state` with `RebuildKind::Vec0`
   376	(`lib.rs:2234-2289`). Codex fix-1 review (finding 1,
   377	`dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-fix-1-review-20260527T134214Z.md`)
   378	correctly flagged that this path:
   379	
   380	- Is asynchronous. `rebuild_shadow_state` only truncates vec0
   381	  state and resets the projection cursor; the actual
   382	  re-derivation runs on the projection scheduler. The test at
   383	  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/rebuild_vec0.rs:80-98`
   384	  observes `rebuild_vec0` returns immediately and polls
   385	  `projection_status_for_test` to wait for the async drain.
   386	- Re-runs the embedder. The projection scheduler's
   387	  `run_projection_job` calls `embedder.embed(&job.body)` at
   388	  `src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/src/lib.rs:2528-2557` for
   389	  every row it re-derives.
   390	- Is therefore not equivalent to copying the existing f32
   391	  blobs: it would multiply the migration cost by the embedder
   392	  work the migration is specifically designed to avoid, and it
   393	  would leak a window in which `vector_default` is empty before
   394	  the async drain catches up.
   395	
   396	The staged-copy migration above replaces this path entirely.
   397	`rebuild_vec0` remains as it is in tree for the operator-driven
   398	"rebuild from canonical" tool; Pack 1's migration does not call
   399	it.
   400	
   401	## D5 — Writer transaction shape
   402	
   403	The writer site is `commit_projection_outcomes` at
   404	`lib.rs:2845-2853`. The double-write lands in the **same**
   405	`tx.execute` sequence between the existing
   406	`_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert and the existing
   407	`record_projection_terminal` call. No extra commit; no extra
   408	lock; no extra connection.
   409	
   410	**Decision: compute `vec_quantize_binary` inside the SQL
   411	statement (single `INSERT` per row), not in Rust ahead of bind.**
